"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136997","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-09","<p>There are a range of options available to help people manage their agoraphobia. The National Health Service website provides information and advice on a range of mental health matters, including panic disorder, and provides access to digital applications through the NHS Apps Library that can support people.</p><p>Lifestyle changes and self-help techniques may help, including taking regular exercise, eating more healthily, and avoiding alcohol, drugs and drinks that contain caffeine. Medication may be recommended by a general practitioner if these are not effective.</p><p>Through the Improving Access to Psychological Therapies programme, people with agoraphobia can also refer themselves directly for psychological therapies, including cognitive behavioural therapy.</p><p>In severe cases of agoraphobia, medication may be used in combination with other types of treatment, such as psychological therapies and relaxation therapy.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-09T13:28:41.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136997/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136997/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136997/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-04","Agoraphobia: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what support his Department provides to help people with agoraphobia to live independently.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","273491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136998","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-07-15","<p>In his appearance at the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Select Committee hearing on 2nd July 2019, the Secretary of State stated our ambition to have a robust licencing scheme in place by February 2020. The new scheme will include provisions for protected sites.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-07-15T16:12:36.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136998/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136998/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136998/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-07-04","Nature Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when he plans to authorise the General Licence for land designated as (a) Special Areas of Conservation and (b) Special Protection Areas.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","273303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136999","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>The consultation on a new legal duty to support a public health approach to preventing and tackling serious violence was launched on 1 April and closed on 28 May. The Government response to the consultation will be published shortly.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-07-09T14:21:11.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136999/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136999/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1136999/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, on what date the Government plans to publish its formal response to the public consultation on a new legal duty to support multi-agency action to tackle serious violence.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","273463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137000","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-09","<p>From 1 April 2019, the number of whole time equivalent (WTE) posts, across both centres, was increased from 11.6 to 19.8 – including a new senior nursing role and 7.2 WTE registered mental health nurse roles. The increase in staff numbers will enable the provision of 24 hours, seven days a week nursing care.</p><p>The number of mental healthcare professionals employed as at the end of June 2019 was 8.6 WTE. These staff work across both the Harmondsworth and the Colnbrook immigration removal centres.</p><p>Recruitment to the newly created posts is ongoing.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-07-09T16:00:00.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137000/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137000/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137000/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-04","Mental Health Services: Detention Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many mental healthcare professionals are employed in (a) Harmondsworth and (b) Colnbrook immigration removal centres.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137001","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>In the year ending March 2019 24,333 individuals entered the detention estate which is the lowest level since comparable records began in 2009. In the same period 71% of detainees were held for 28 days or less and 93% for less than four months.</p><p>The Government expects that changes in policy and operational approaches will lead to a reduction in the number of those detained, and the duration of detention before removal, in turn improving the welfare of those detained.</p><p>The Government is committed to using detention sparingly and only when necessary. The Home Office has taken a systematic approach to modernising and rationalising the immigration detention estate, ensuring the geographical footprint and resilience required to meet our future needs. By this summer the estate will be almost 40% smaller than it was four years ago and of significantly higher quality.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","273421","2019-07-09T11:26:15.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137001/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137001/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137001/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans he has to reduce the number of people held in UK immigration removal centres.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137002","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>In the year ending March 2019 24,333 individuals entered the detention estate which is the lowest level since comparable records began in 2009. In the same period 71% of detainees were held for 28 days or less and 93% for less than four months.</p><p>The Government expects that changes in policy and operational approaches will lead to a reduction in the number of those detained, and the duration of detention before removal, in turn improving the welfare of those detained.</p><p>The Government is committed to using detention sparingly and only when necessary. The Home Office has taken a systematic approach to modernising and rationalising the immigration detention estate, ensuring the geographical footprint and resilience required to meet our future needs. By this summer the estate will be almost 40% smaller than it was four years ago and of significantly higher quality.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","273420","2019-07-09T11:26:16.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137002/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137002/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Detention Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans he has to change the provision of immigration removal centres in the UK; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137003","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>We will publish information on the number of claims submitted, number of claims paid and the overall amount paid out by the scheme in due course as part of our regular reporting to the Home Affairs Select Committee.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-09T15:18:14.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137003/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137003/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137003/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people have applied for compensation from the Windrush compensation scheme to date.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137004","Department for Education","false","2019-07-09","<p>The department is investing up to £26 million in a breakfast club programme, using funds from the Soft Drinks Industry Levy revenues. This money will kick-start or improve breakfast clubs in over 1,700 schools. The focus of these clubs has been to target the most disadvantaged areas of the country – including the Department for Education’s Opportunity Areas – to help make sure every child gets the best start in life.</p><p>A contract was awarded to Family Action in March 2018 and will run until March 2020. Family Action, in partnership with Magic Breakfast, have been named as the leading charities responsible for running the breakfast club programme. Family Action are distributing the appropriate funding to participating schools who meet the eligibility criteria. In March 2019, Family Action indicated that by the start of the summer term, over 250,000 children would be benefiting from the programme.</p><p>The programme is available to primary schools, as well as secondary schools, special schools and pupil referral units that are eligible to take part. We monitor management information from the programme on an ongoing basis and will also review the effectiveness of the programme fully once the programme concludes.</p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-07-09T11:51:42.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137004/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137004/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137004/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-07-04","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of funding to support breakfast clubs in primary schools.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","273492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137005","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>Officials in the Home Office continue to work closely with the DWP and HMRC on the design and delivery of the compensation scheme but also on individual cases through the Taskforce. The joint working has enabled those with a right to benefits to have them re-instated.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-09T15:18:48.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137005/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137005/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137005/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions on the effect of a wrong decision being made denying a person the right to re-enter the UK under the Windrush scandal on eligibility for benefits and tax credits which require residency in the UK for the last two years.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137006","Home Office","false","2019-07-09","<p>We will publish information on the number of claims submitted, number of claims paid and the overall amount paid out by the scheme in due course as part of our regular reporting to the Home Affairs Select Committee.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-07-09T15:17:41.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137006/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137006/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137006/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-07-04","Immigration: Windrush Generation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many applications for compensation by people affected by the Windrush scandal have been successful, and how many of those successful applicants have received compensation.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","273424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137007","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-07-10","<p>There is no administrative data held that could determine the reasons why an individual, if dissatisfied with the decision received after their MR is completed, might not choose to pursue an appeal with HMCTS.</p><p> </p><p>There is already some data in the public domain that may be of interest. The Personal Independent Payment (PIP) Official Statistics holds information on the volumes of Mandatory Reconsiderations (MRs) registered (<em>Table 7A</em>) and cleared (<em>Table 7B</em>), and can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2019</a></p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice Tribunal Statistics Quarterly publication contains the number of PIP cases for which an appeal is lodged with Her Majesty’s Courts and Tribunal Service (HMCTS) (<em>Table SSCS1</em>), and can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/tribunal-statistics-quarterly-january-to-march-2019</a></p><p> </p><p>HM Courts and Tribunals Service (HCMTS) is taking positive steps to reduce the waiting time for appeals to be heard in the Social Security and Child Support (SSCS) jurisdiction. In 2018, 232 medical members and 118 disability-qualified members were additionally appointed to the SSCS jurisdiction and an extra 129 fee-paid judges have recently been appointed. The SSCS jurisdiction will also benefit from 100 salaried judges and 170 fee-paid judges being recruited across tribunals more widely. In addition, HMCTS is developing a new digital system with a view to enabling speedier processing of appeals and a better service for all parties to the proceedings. Case-management “triage” sessions are also being conducted, with the aim of reducing the number of cases that need to progress to an oral hearing.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-07-10T15:18:58.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137007/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137007/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137007/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-07-04","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who decided not to pursue an appeal for personal independence payments due to the length of the waiting time for an appeal.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","273493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137008","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-07-10","<p>HM Courts and Tribunals Service (HCMTS) is taking positive steps to reduce the waiting time for appeals to be heard in the Social Security and Child Support (SSCS) jurisdiction. In 2018, 232 medical members and 118 disability-qualified members were additionally appointed to the SSCS jurisdiction and an extra 129 fee-paid judges have recently been appointed. The SSCS jurisdiction will also benefit from 100 salaried judges and 170 fee-paid judges being recruited across tribunals more widely. In addition, HMCTS is developing a new digital system with a view to enabling speedier processing of appeals and a better service for all parties to the proceedings. Case-management “triage” sessions are also being conducted, with the aim of reducing the number of cases that need to progress to an oral hearing.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2019-07-10T16:32:41.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137008/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137008/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137008/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-07-04","Personal Independence Payment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of whether the HM Courts and Tribunals service has the capacity to reduce the waiting time for an appeal for personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","273494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137009","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-07-12","<p>We remain deeply concerned by Hamas's attempts to re-arm and rebuild militant infrastructure, including the tunnel network, in Gaza. Such actions undermine efforts to improve the situation in Gaza and harm the prospects for peace. During my visit to Israel at the end of May, I witnessed first-hand the impact of Hamas tunnels and rockets on the Israeli communities close to Gaza.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-07-12T10:33:28.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137009/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137009/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137009/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-07-04","Israel: Gaza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the threat posed to Israel by cross-border tunnels dug by Hamas.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Djanogly","Huntingdon","Mr Jonathan Djanogly","273340"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137010","Department for Transport","false","2019-07-09","<p>The Department for Transport does not hold the data requested.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-07-09T14:13:55.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137010/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137010/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137010/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-07-04","Great Western Railway: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on how many occasions Great Western trains ran with reduced carriage numbers as a result of a shortage of sets in each month since the introduction of the new trains in October 2017.","false","Biography information for Dr David Drew","Stroud","Dr David Drew","273317"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137011","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-07-09","<p>Since 2011 the Department has provided over £26.8 million in financial support to NHS Blood and Transplant and Anthony Nolan to enable the establishment of a unified United Kingdom Stem Cell Registry and improve access to and outcomes of stem cell donation. This includes improving equity of access to unrelated donor stem cell transplantation for black, Asian and minority ethnic (BAME) patients through targeted recruitment to the UK Stem Cell Registry and the Department has set specific targets about the proportion of donors that must be from BAME backgrounds.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-07-09T12:56:21.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137011/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137011/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1137011/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-07-04","Stem Cells: Donors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to increase BAME recruitment to the stem cell registry.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","273333"
